# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: suffix-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] In computer science, a **generalized suffix tree** is a suffix tree for a set of strings.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] Given the set of strings $D=S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{d}$ of total length n , it is a Patricia tree containing all n suffixes of the strings.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] It can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time and space, and can be used to find all z occurrences of a string P of length m in $O(m+z)$ time, which is asymptotically optimal (assuming the size of the alphabet is constant).
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] When constructing such a tree, each string should be padded with a unique out-of-alphabet marker symbol (or string) to ensure no suffix is a substring of another, guaranteeing each suffix is represented by a unique leaf node.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] Algorithms for constructing a GST include Ukkonen's algorithm (1995) and McCreight's algorithm (1976).
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] A suffix tree for the strings `ABAB` and `BABA` is shown in a figure above.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] They are padded with the unique terminator strings `$0` and `$1`.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] The numbers in the leaf nodes are string number and starting position.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] Notice how a left to right traversal of the leaf nodes corresponds to the sorted order of the suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] The terminators might be strings or unique single symbols.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] Edges on `$` from the root are left out in this example.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] An alternative to building a generalized suffix tree is to concatenate the strings, and build a regular suffix tree or suffix array for the resulting string.
[src:suffix-tree/generalized-suffix-tree] When hits are evaluated after a search, global positions are mapped into documents and local positions with some algorithm and/or data structure, such as a binary search in the starting/ending positions of the documents.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] In computer science, a **suffix array** is a sorted array of all suffixes of a string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] It is a data structure used in, among others, full-text indices, data-compression algorithms, and the field of bibliometrics.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Suffix arrays were introduced by Manber & Myers (1990) as a simple, space efficient alternative to suffix trees.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] They had independently been discovered by Gaston Gonnet in 1987 under the name *PAT array* (Gonnet, Baeza-Yates & Snider 1992).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Li, Li & Huo (2016) gave the first in-place ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time suffix array construction algorithm that is optimal both in time and space, where *in-place* means that the algorithm only needs ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ additional space beyond the input string and the output suffix array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Enhanced suffix arrays (ESAs) are suffix arrays with additional tables that reproduce the full functionality of suffix trees preserving the same time and memory complexity.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] A sorted array of only some (rather than all) suffixes of a string is called a sparse suffix array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Let $S=S[1]S[2]...S[n]$ be an ${\textstyle n}$ -string and let $S[i,j]$ denote the substring of S ranging from i to j inclusive.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The suffix array A of S is now defined to be an array of integers providing the starting positions of suffixes of S in lexicographical order.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] This means, an entry $A[i]$ contains the starting position of the i -th smallest suffix in S and thus for all $1\leq i\leq n$ : $S[A[i-1],n]<S[A[i],n]$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Each suffix of S shows up in A exactly once.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] These strings are sorted (as in a paper dictionary), before their starting positions (integer indices) are saved in A .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The text ends with the special sentinel letter `$` that is unique and lexicographically smaller than any other character.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] So for example, $A[3]$ contains the value 4, and therefore refers to the suffix starting at position 4 within S , which is the suffix `ana$`.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] It has been shown that every suffix tree algorithm can be systematically replaced with an algorithm that uses a suffix array enhanced with additional information (such as the LCP array) and solves the same problem in the same time complexity.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Advantages of suffix arrays over suffix trees include improved space requirements, simpler linear time construction algorithms (e.g., compared to Ukkonen's algorithm) and improved cache locality.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Suffix arrays were introduced by Manber & Myers (1990) in order to improve over the space requirements of suffix trees: Suffix arrays store n integers.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Assuming an integer requires 4 bytes, a suffix array requires $4n$ bytes in total.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] This is significantly less than the $20n$ bytes which are required by a careful suffix tree implementation.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] However, in certain applications, the space requirements of suffix arrays may still be prohibitive.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Analyzed in bits, a suffix array requires ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ space, whereas the original text over an alphabet of size $\sigma$ only requires ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log \sigma )$ bits.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] For a human genome with $\sigma =4$ and $n=3.4\times 10^{9}$ the suffix array would therefore occupy about 16 times more memory than the genome itself.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Such discrepancies motivated a trend towards compressed suffix arrays and BWT-based compressed full-text indices such as the FM-index.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] These data structures require only space within the size of the text or even less.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] A suffix tree can be built in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ and can be converted into a suffix array by traversing the tree depth-first also in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ , so there exist algorithms that can build a suffix array in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] A naive approach to construct a suffix array is to use a comparison-based sorting algorithm.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] These algorithms require ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ suffix comparisons, but a suffix comparison runs in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time, so the overall runtime of this approach is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] More advanced algorithms take advantage of the fact that the suffixes to be sorted are not arbitrary strings but related to each other.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] One of the first algorithms to achieve all goals is the SA-IS algorithm of Nong, Zhang & Chan (2009).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The algorithm is also rather simple (< 100 LOC) and can be enhanced to simultaneously construct the LCP array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The SA-IS algorithm is one of the fastest known suffix array construction algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] A careful implementation by Yuta Mori outperforms most other linear or super-linear construction approaches.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] A well-known recursive algorithm for integer alphabets is the *DC3 / skew* algorithm of Kärkkäinen & Sanders (2003).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] It runs in linear time and has successfully been used as the basis for parallel and external memory suffix array construction algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] (2010) proposes an algorithm for updating the suffix array of a text that has been edited instead of rebuilding a new suffix array from scratch.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] In practical open source work, a commonly used routine for suffix array construction was qsufsort, based on the 1999 Larsson-Sadakane algorithm.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] This routine has been superseded by Yuta Mori's DivSufSort, "the fastest known suffix sorting algorithm in main memory" as of 2017.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] It too can be modified to compute an LCP array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] It uses a induced copying combined with Itoh-Tanaka.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] In 2021 a faster implementation of the algorithm was presented by Ilya Grebnov which in average showed 65% performance improvement over DivSufSort implementation on the Silesia corpus.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The concept of a suffix array can be extended to more than one string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] This is called a generalized suffix array (or GSA), a suffix array that contains all suffixes for a set of strings (for example, $S=S_{1},S_{2},S_{3},...,S_{k}$ and is lexicographically sorted with all suffixes of each string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The suffix array of a string can be used as an index to quickly locate every occurrence of a substring pattern P within the string S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Finding every occurrence of the pattern is equivalent to finding every suffix that begins with the substring.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Thanks to the lexicographical ordering, these suffixes will be grouped together in the suffix array and can be found efficiently with two binary searches.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Finding the substring pattern P of length m in the string S of length n takes ${\mathcal {O}}(m\log n)$ time, given that a single suffix comparison needs to compare m characters.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Manber & Myers (1990) describe how this bound can be improved to ${\mathcal {O}}(m+\log n)$ time using LCP information.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The idea is that a pattern comparison does not need to re-compare certain characters, when it is already known that these are part of the longest common prefix of the pattern and the current search interval.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Abouelhoda, Kurtz & Ohlebusch (2004) improve the bound even further and achieve a search time of ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ for constant alphabet size, as known from suffix trees.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Suffix sorting algorithms can be used to compute the Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The BWT requires sorting of all cyclic permutations of a string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] If this string ends in a special end-of-string character that is lexicographically smaller than all other character (i.e., $), then the order of the sorted rotated BWT matrix corresponds to the order of suffixes in a suffix array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The BWT can therefore be computed in linear time by first constructing a suffix array of the text and then deducing the BWT string: $BWT[i]=S[A[i]-1]$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Suffix arrays can also be used to look up substrings in example-based machine translation, demanding much less storage than a full phrase table as used in Statistical machine translation.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Many additional applications of the suffix array require the LCP array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Some of these are detailed in the application section of the latter.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Suffix trees are powerful data structures that have wide application in areas of pattern and string matching, indexing and textual statistics.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] However, it occupies a significant amount of space and thus has a drawback in many real-time applications that require processing a considerably large amount of data like genome analysis.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] To overcome this drawback, the Enhanced Suffix Array was developed.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] It is a data structure consisting of a suffix array and an additional table called the child table that contains the information about the parent-child relationship between the nodes in the suffix tree.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The node branching data structure for this tree is a linked list.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Enhanced suffix arrays are superior to suffix trees in terms of both space efficiency and time complexity and are easy to implement.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Moreover, they can be applied to any algorithm that uses a suffix tree by using an abstract concept called LCP-interval trees.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The time complexity for searching a pattern of length m in an enhanced suffix array is ${\mathcal {O}}(m|\Sigma |)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] 2. lcp array lcp[1,...n]: It is an array of n integers that maintains the lengths of the longest common prefix of two consecutive suffixes stored in the pos array.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The length of the longest common prefix of pos[i − 1] and pos[i] is stored in lcp[i],where 2 ≤ i ≤ n.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The lcp-interval portrays the same parent-child relationship as that among the associated nodes in the suffix tree of S.This shows that if the corresponding node of [i..j] is a child of the corresponding node of [k..l], a lcp-interval [i..j] is a child interval of another lcp-interval [k..l].
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] If [k..l] is a child interval of [i..j], a lcp-interval [i..j] is the parent interval of a lcp-interval [k..l].
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The child table *cldtab* is composed of three n arrays, *up*, *down* and *nextlIndex*.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The information about the edges of the corresponding suffix tree is stored and maintained by the *up* and *down* arrays.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The *nextlIndex* array stores the links in the linked list used for node branching the suffix tree.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The initial index of the second child interval of the longest lcp-interval, starting at index *i* is stored in the element *down[i]*.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] If and only if the interval is neither the first child nor the final child of its parent, the element *nextlIndex[i]* contains the first index of the next sibling interval of the longest lcp-interval, starting at index *i*.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] By performing a bottom-up traversal of the lcp-interval of the tree, the child table can be constructed in linear time.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The *up/down* values and the *nextlIndex* values can be computed separately by using two distinct algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The suffix links for an enhanced suffix array can be computed by generating the suffix link interval [*1,..,r*] for each [i,..j] interval during the preprocessing.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The left and right elements l and r of the interval are maintained in the first index of [i,..,j].
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The table for this interval ranges from 0 to n.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The suffix link table is constructed by the left-to-right breadth-first traversal of the lcp-interval tree.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] Every time an *l*-interval is computed, it is added to the list of l-intervals, which is referred to as the l-list.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] When the lcp-value > 0, for every *l*-interval[i,..,j] in the list, link[i] is calculated.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The interval [*l*,..,*r*] is computed by a binary search in(*l*-1)-list, where *l* is the largest left boundary amongst all the *l*-1 intervals.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The suffix link interval of [i,..j] is represented by this interval[*l,..,r*].
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-array] The values *l* and *r* are ultimately stored in the first index of [i,..,j].
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In computer science, a **suffix automaton** is an efficient data structure for representing the substring index of a given string which allows the storage, processing, and retrieval of compressed information about all its substrings.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The suffix automaton of a string S is the smallest directed acyclic graph with a dedicated initial vertex and a set of "final" vertices, such that paths from the initial vertex to final vertices represent the suffixes of the string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In terms of automata theory, a suffix automaton is the minimal partial deterministic finite automaton that recognizes the set of suffixes of a given string $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The state graph of a suffix automaton is called a directed acyclic word graph (DAWG), a term that is also sometimes used for any deterministic acyclic finite state automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata were introduced in 1983 by a group of scientists from the University of Denver and the University of Colorado Boulder.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] They suggested a linear time online algorithm for its construction and showed that the suffix automaton of a string S having length at least two characters has at most ${\textstyle 2|S|-1}$ states and at most ${\textstyle 3|S|-4}$ transitions.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Further works have shown a close connection between suffix automata and suffix trees, and have outlined several generalizations of suffix automata, such as compacted suffix automaton obtained by compression of nodes with a single outgoing arc.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata provide efficient solutions to problems such as substring search and computation of the largest common substring of two and more strings.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In their initial work, Blumer *et al*. showed a suffix automaton built for the string S of length greater than 1 has at most $2|S|-1$ states and at most $3|S|-4$ transitions, and suggested a linear algorithm for automaton construction.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In 1983, Mu-Tian Chen and Joel Seiferas independently showed that Weiner's 1973 suffix-tree construction algorithm while building a suffix tree of the string S constructs a suffix automaton of the reversed string ${\textstyle S^{R}}$ as an auxiliary structure.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In 1987, Blumer *et al*. applied the compressing technique used in suffix trees to a suffix automaton and invented the compacted suffix automaton, which is also called the compacted directed acyclic word graph (CDAWG).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In 1997, Maxime Crochemore and Renaud Vérin developed a linear algorithm for direct CDAWG construction.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In 2001, Shunsuke Inenaga *et al*. developed an algorithm for construction of CDAWG for a set of words given by a trie.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In terms of its diagram, the automaton recognizes the word $\omega =\omega _{1}\omega _{2}\dots \omega _{m}$ only if there is a path from the initial vertex $q_{0}$ to some final vertex $q\in F$ such that concatenation of characters on this path forms $\omega$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The set of words recognized by an automaton forms a language that is set to be recognized by the automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In these terms, the language recognized by a suffix automaton of S is the language of its (possibly empty) suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] "Right context" of the word $\omega$ with respect to language L is a set $[\omega ]_{R}=\{\alpha :\omega \alpha \in L\}$ that is a set of words $\alpha$ such that their concatenation with $\omega$ forms a word from L .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Right contexts induce a natural equivalence relation $[\alpha ]_{R}=[\beta ]_{R}$ on the set of all words.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] If language L is recognized by some deterministic finite automaton, there exists unique up to isomorphism automaton that recognizes the same language and has the minimum possible number of states.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Such an automaton is called a minimal automaton for the given language L .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In these terms, a "suffix automaton" is the minimal deterministic finite automaton recognizing the language of suffixes of the word $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The right context of the word $\omega$ with respect to this language consists of words $\alpha$ , such that $\omega \alpha$ is a suffix of S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] For example, for the word $S=abacaba$ and its subword $\omega =ab$ , it holds $endpos(ab)=\{2,6\}$ and $[ab]_{R}=\{a,acaba\}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Informally, $[ab]_{R}$ is formed by words that follow occurrences of $ab$ to the end of S and $endpos(ab)$ is formed by right positions of those occurrences.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In this example, the element $x=2\in endpos(ab)$ corresponds with the word $s_{3}s_{4}s_{5}s_{6}s_{7}=acaba\in [ab]_{R}$ while the word $a\in [ab]_{R}$ corresponds with the element $7-|a|=6\in endpos(ab)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It implies several structure properties of suffix automaton states.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Any state $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ of the suffix automaton recognizes some continuous chain of nested suffixes of the longest word recognized by this state.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] "Left extension" ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\gamma }}$ of the string $\gamma$ is the longest string $\omega$ that has the same right context as $\gamma$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Length $|{\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\gamma }}|$ of the longest string recognized by $q=[\gamma ]_{R}$ is denoted by $len(q)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] "Suffix link" $link(q)$ of the state $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ is the pointer to the state p that contains the largest suffix of $\alpha$ that is not recognized by q .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In this terms it can be said $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ recognizes exactly all suffixes of ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\alpha }}$ that is longer than $len(link(q))$ and not longer than $len(q)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Edges E of the tree connect pairs of vertices $({\overleftarrow {\omega }},{\overleftarrow {\alpha \omega }})$ , such that $\alpha \in \Sigma$ and ${\overleftarrow {\omega }}\neq {\overleftarrow {\alpha \omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] A "prefix tree" (or "trie") is a rooted directed tree in which arcs are marked by characters in such a way no vertex v of such tree has two out-going arcs marked with the same character.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Some vertices in trie are marked as final.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Trie is said to recognize a set of words defined by paths from its root to final vertices.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In this way prefix trees are a special kind of deterministic finite automata if you perceive its root as an initial vertex.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The "suffix trie" of the word S is a prefix tree recognizing a set of its suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] "A suffix tree" is a tree obtained from a suffix trie via the compaction procedure, during which consequent edges are merged if the degree of the vertex between them is equal to two.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] By its definition, a suffix automaton can be obtained via minimization of the suffix trie.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It may be shown that a compacted suffix automaton is obtained by both minimization of the suffix tree (if one assumes each string on the edge of the suffix tree is a solid character from the alphabet) and compaction of the suffix automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Besides this connection between the suffix tree and the suffix automaton of the same string there is as well a connection between the suffix automaton of the string $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ and the suffix tree of the reversed string $S^{R}=s_{n}s_{n-1}\dots s_{1}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] A suffix automaton of the string S of length $n>1$ has at most $2n-1$ states and at most $3n-4$ transitions.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] These bounds are reached on strings $abb\dots bb=ab^{n-1}$ and $abb\dots bc=ab^{n-2}c$ correspondingly.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] This may be formulated in a stricter way as $|\delta |\leq |Q|+n-2$ where $|\delta |$ and $|Q|$ are the numbers of transitions and states in automaton correspondingly.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Initially the automaton only consists of a single state corresponding to the empty word, then characters of the string are added one by one and the automaton is rebuilt on each step incrementally.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] After a new character is appended to the string, some equivalence classes are altered.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Let $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ be the right context of $\alpha$ with respect to the language of $\omega$ suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] After adding x to the current word $\omega$ the right context of $\alpha$ may change significantly only if $\alpha$ is a suffix of $\omega x$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It implies equivalence relation $\equiv _{R_{\omega x}}$ is a refinement of $\equiv _{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] After the addition of a new character at most two equivalence classes of $\equiv _{R_{\omega }}$ will be split and each of them may split in at most two new classes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] First, equivalence class corresponding to empty right context is always split into two equivalence classes, one of them corresponding to $\omega x$ itself and having $\{\varepsilon \}$ as a right context.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] This new equivalence class contains exactly $\omega x$ and all its suffixes that did not occur in $\omega$ , as the right context of such words was empty before and contains only empty word now.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Given the correspondence between states of the suffix automaton and vertices of the suffix tree, it is possible to find out the second state that may possibly split after a new character is appended.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The transition from $\omega$ to $\omega x$ corresponds to the transition from $\omega ^{R}$ to $x\omega ^{R}$ in the reversed string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In terms of suffix trees it corresponds to the insertion of the new longest suffix $x\omega ^{R}$ into the suffix tree of $\omega ^{R}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] At most two new vertices may be formed after this insertion: one of them corresponding to $x\omega ^{R}$ , while the other one corresponds to its direct ancestor if there was a branching.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Returning to suffix automata, it means the first new state recognizes $\omega x$ and the second one (if there is a second new state) is its suffix link.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It implies that if $\alpha =\beta$ (for example, when x didn't occur in $\omega$ at all and $\alpha =\beta =\varepsilon$ ), then only the equivalence class corresponding to the empty right context is split.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Besides suffix links it is also needed to define final states of the automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It follows from structure properties that all suffixes of a word $\alpha$ recognized by $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ are recognized by some vertex on *suffix path* $(q,link(q),link^{2}(q),\dots )$ of q .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Namely, suffixes with length greater than $len(link(q))$ lie in q , suffixes with length greater than $len(link(link(q))$ but not greater than $len(link(q))$ lie in $link(q)$ and so on.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Thus if the state recognizing $\omega$ is denoted by $last$ , then all final states (that is, recognizing suffixes of $\omega$ ) form up the sequence $(last,link(last),link^{2}(last),\dots )$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] After the character x is appended to $\omega$ possible new states of suffix automaton are $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ and $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Words from $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ occur in $\omega x$ only as its suffixes therefore there should be no transitions at all from $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ while transitions to it should go from suffixes of $\omega$ having length at least $\alpha$ and be marked with the character x .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] State $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ is formed by subset of $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ , thus transitions from $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ should be same as from $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Meanwhile, transitions leading to $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ should go from suffixes of $\omega$ having length less than $|\alpha |$ and at least $len(link([\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}))$ , as such transitions have led to $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ before and corresponded to seceded part of this state.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] States corresponding to these suffixes may be determined via traversal of suffix link path for $[\omega ]_{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] States corresponding to suffixes of ω are updated with transitions to last.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Transitions that have led to q before but corresponded to words of the length at most $len(p)+1$ are redirected to cl.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] To do this, one continues going through the suffix path of p until the state is found such that transition by x from it doesn't lead to q.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Here $q_{0}$ is the initial state of the automaton and `new_state()` is a function creating new state for it.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It is assumed `*last*`, `*len*`, `*link*` and `δ` are stored as global variables.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] For convenience, `*link(q0)*` is defined to be $q_{0}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Complexity of the algorithm may vary depending on the underlying structure used to store transitions of the automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It may be implemented in $O(n\log |\Sigma |)$ with $O(n)$ memory overhead or in $O(n)$ with $O(n|\Sigma |)$ memory overhead if one assumes that memory allocation is done in $O(1)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] To obtain such complexity, one has to use the methods of amortized analysis.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The value of $len(p)$ strictly reduces with each iteration of the cycle while it may only increase by as much as one after the first iteration of the cycle on the next *add_letter* call.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Overall value of $len(p)$ never exceeds n and it is only increased by one between iterations of appending new letters that suggest total complexity is at most linear as well.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The linearity of the second cycle is shown in a similar way.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The suffix automaton is closely related to other suffix structures and substring indices.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Given a suffix automaton of a specific string one may construct its suffix tree via compacting and recursive traversal in linear time.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Similar transforms are possible in both directions to switch between the suffix automaton of S and the suffix tree of reversed string $S^{R}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] As was already mentioned above, a compacted suffix automaton is obtained via both compaction of a regular suffix automaton (by removing states which are non-final and have exactly one out-going arc) and the minimization of a suffix tree.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Similarly to the regular suffix automaton, states of compacted suffix automaton may be defined in explicit manner.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] *A two-way extension* ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\longleftrightarrow }}{\gamma }}$ of a word $\gamma$ is the longest word $\omega =\beta \gamma \alpha$ , such that every occurrence of $\gamma$ in S is preceded by $\beta$ and succeeded by $\alpha$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Two-way extensions induce an equivalence relation ${\textstyle {\overset {\scriptstyle \longleftrightarrow }{\alpha }}={\overset {\scriptstyle \longleftrightarrow }{\beta }}}$ which defines the set of words recognized by the same state of compacted automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] If words $\alpha$ and $\beta$ have same right extensions, and words $\beta$ and $\gamma$ have same left extensions, then cumulatively all strings $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\gamma$ have same two-way extensions.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] At the same time it may happen that neither left nor right extensions of $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ coincide.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The total number of equivalence classes for this relation does not exceed $n+1$ which implies that compacted suffix automaton of the string having length n has at most $n+1$ states.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The amount of transitions in such automaton is at most $2n-2$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It is possible to construct a generalization of suffix automaton that would recognize the language formed up by suffixes of all words from the set.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Constraints for the number of states and transitions in such automaton would stay the same as for a single-word automaton if you put $n=|S_{1}|+|S_{2}|+\dots +|S_{k}|$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] This idea is further generalized to the case when T is not given explicitly but instead is given by a prefix tree with Q vertices.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Mohri *et al*. showed such an automaton would have at most $2Q-2$ and may be constructed in linear time from its size.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Some compression algorithms, such as LZ77 and RLE may benefit from storing suffix automaton or similar structure not for the whole string but for only last k its characters while the string is updated.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] This is because compressing data is usually expressively large and using $O(n)$ memory is undesirable.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] In 1985, Janet Blumer developed an algorithm to maintain a suffix automaton on a sliding window of size k in $O(nk)$ worst-case and $O(n\log k)$ on average, assuming characters are distributed independently and uniformly.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] A variation of McCreight's suffix tree construction algorithm for this task was suggested in 1989 by Edward Fiala and Daniel Greene; several years later a similar result was obtained with the variation of Ukkonen's algorithm by Jesper Larsson.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] One way to overcome this obstacle is to allow window width to vary a bit while staying $O(k)$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It may be achieved by an approximate algorithm suggested by Inenaga et al. in 2004.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] The window for which suffix automaton is built in this algorithm is not guaranteed to be of length k but it is guaranteed to be at least k and at most $2k+1$ while providing linear overall complexity of the algorithm.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] It is assumed here that T is given on the input after suffix automaton of S is constructed.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata are also used in data compression, music retrieval and matching on genome sequences.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] In computer science, a **suffix tree** (also called **PAT tree** or, in an earlier form, **position tree**) is a compressed trie containing all the suffixes of the given text as their keys and positions in the text as their values.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees allow particularly fast implementations of many important string operations.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The construction of such a tree for the string S takes time and space linear in the length of S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Once constructed, several operations can be performed quickly, such as locating a substring in S , locating a substring if a certain number of mistakes are allowed, and locating matches for a regular expression pattern.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees also provided one of the first linear-time solutions for the longest common substring problem.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] These speedups come at a cost: storing a string's suffix tree typically requires significantly more space than storing the string itself.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The concept was first introduced by Weiner (1973).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Rather than the suffix $S[i..n]$ , Weiner stored in his trie the *prefix identifier* for each position, that is, the shortest string starting at i and occurring only once in S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] His *Algorithm D* takes an uncompressed trie for $S[k+1..n]$ and extends it into a trie for $S[k..n]$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] This way, starting from the trivial trie for $S[n..n]$ , a trie for $S[1..n]$ can be built by $n-1$ successive calls to Algorithm D; however, the overall run time is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Weiner's *Algorithm B* maintains several auxiliary data structures, to achieve an overall run time linear in the size of the constructed trie.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The latter can still be $O(n^{2})$ nodes, e.g. for $S=a^{n}b^{n}a^{n}b^{n}\$.$ Weiner's *Algorithm C* finally uses compressed tries to achieve linear overall storage size and run time.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Donald Knuth subsequently characterized the latter as "Algorithm of the Year 1973" according to his student Vaughan Pratt.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The text book Aho, Hopcroft & Ullman (1974, Sect.9.5) reproduced Weiner's results in a simplified and more elegant form, introducing the term *position tree*.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] McCreight (1976) was the first to build a (compressed) trie of all suffixes of S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Although the suffix starting at i is usually longer than the prefix identifier, their path representations in a compressed trie do not differ in size.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] On the other hand, McCreight could dispense with most of Weiner's auxiliary data structures; only suffix links remained.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Ukkonen (1995) further simplified the construction.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] He provided the first online-construction of suffix trees, now known as Ukkonen's algorithm, with running time that matched the then fastest algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] These algorithms are all linear-time for a constant-size alphabet, and have worst-case running time of $O(n\log n)$ in general.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Farach (1997) gave the first suffix tree construction algorithm that is optimal for all alphabets.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] In particular, this is the first linear-time algorithm for strings drawn from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Farach's algorithm has become the basis for new algorithms for constructing both suffix trees and suffix arrays, for example, in external memory, compressed, succinct, etc.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Except for the root, every internal node has at least two children.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Each edge is labelled with a non-empty substring of S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] No two edges starting out of a node can have string-labels beginning with the same character.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The string obtained by concatenating all the string-labels found on the path from the root to leaf i spells out suffix $S[i..n]$ , for i from 1 to n .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] If a suffix of S is also the prefix of another suffix, such a tree does not exist for the string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] For example, in the string *abcbc*, the suffix *bc* is also a prefix of the suffix *bcbc*.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] In such a case, the path spelling out *bc* will not end in a leaf, violating the fifth rule.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] To fix this problem, S is padded with a terminal symbol not seen in the string (usually denoted `$`).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] This ensures that no suffix is a prefix of another, and that there will be n leaf nodes, one for each of the n suffixes of S .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Since all internal non-root nodes are branching, there can be at most $n-1$ such nodes, and $n+(n-1)+1=2n$ nodes in total ( n leaves, $n-1$ internal non-root nodes, 1 root).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] A generalized suffix tree is a suffix tree made for a set of strings instead of a single string.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] It represents all suffixes from this set of strings.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Each string must be terminated by a different termination symbol.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] A suffix tree for a string S of length n can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, if the letters come from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range (in particular, this is true for constant-sized alphabets).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] For larger alphabets, the running time is dominated by first sorting the letters to bring them into a range of size $O(n)$ ; in general, this takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The costs below are given under the assumption that the alphabet is constant.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Assume that a suffix tree has been built for the string S of length n , or that a generalised suffix tree has been built for the set of strings $D=\{S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{K}\}$ of total length $n=n_{1}+n_{2}+\cdots +n_{K}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The suffix tree can be prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval between nodes in $\Theta (n)$ time.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees can be used to solve a large number of string problems that occur in text-editing, free-text search, computational biology and other application areas.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are often used in bioinformatics applications, searching for patterns in DNA or protein sequences (which can be viewed as long strings of characters).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The ability to search efficiently with mismatches might be considered their greatest strength.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are also used in data compression; they can be used to find repeated data, and can be used for the sorting stage of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Variants of the LZW compression schemes use suffix trees (LZSS).
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] A suffix tree is also used in suffix tree clustering, a data clustering algorithm used in some search engines.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] If each node and edge can be represented in $\Theta (1)$ space, the entire tree can be represented in $\Theta (n)$ space.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The total length of all the strings on all of the edges in the tree is $O(n^{2})$ , but each edge can be stored as the position and length of a substring of S, giving a total space usage of $\Theta (n)$ computer words.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The worst-case space usage of a suffix tree is seen with a fibonacci word, giving the full $2n$ nodes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] An important choice when making a suffix tree implementation is the parent-child relationships between nodes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The most common is using linked lists called **sibling lists**.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Each node has a pointer to its first child, and to the next node in the child list it is a part of.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Other implementations with efficient running time properties use hash maps, sorted or unsorted arrays (with array doubling), or balanced search trees.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The insertion cost is amortised, and that the costs for hashing are given for perfect hashing.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The large amount of information in each edge and node makes the suffix tree very expensive, consuming about 10 to 20 times the memory size of the source text in good implementations.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Researchers have continued to find smaller indexing structures.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Various parallel algorithms to speed up suffix tree construction have been proposed.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Recently, a practical parallel algorithm for suffix tree construction with $O(n)$ work (sequential time) and $O(\log ^{2}n)$ span has been developed.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The algorithm achieves good parallel scalability on shared-memory multicore machines and can index the human genome – approximately 3GB – in under 3 minutes using a 40-core machine.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] Though linear, the memory usage of a suffix tree is significantly higher than the actual size of the sequence collection.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] For a large text, construction may require external memory approaches.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] There are theoretical results for constructing suffix trees in external memory.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The algorithm by Farach-Colton, Ferragina & Muthukrishnan (2000) is theoretically optimal, with an I/O complexity equal to that of sorting.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] However the overall intricacy of this algorithm has prevented, so far, its practical implementation.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] On the other hand, there have been practical works for constructing disk-based suffix trees which scale to (few) GB/hours.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The state of the art methods are TDD, TRELLIS, DiGeST, and B2ST.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] TDD and TRELLIS scale up to the entire human genome resulting in a disk-based suffix tree of a size in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] However, these methods cannot handle efficiently collections of sequences exceeding 3 GB.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] DiGeST performs significantly better and is able to handle collections of sequences in the order of 6 GB in about 6 hours.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] All these methods can efficiently build suffix trees for the case when the tree does not fit in main memory, but the input does.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] The most recent method, B2ST, scales to handle inputs that do not fit in main memory.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] ERA is a recent parallel suffix tree construction method that is significantly faster.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] ERA can index the entire human genome in 19 minutes on an 8-core desktop computer with 16 GB RAM.
[src:suffix-tree/suffix-tree] On a simple Linux cluster with 16 nodes (4 GB RAM per node), ERA can index the entire human genome in less than 9 minutes.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A prefix trie is an ordered tree data structure used in the representation of a set of strings over a finite alphabet set, which allows efficient storage of words with common prefixes.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries can be efficacious on string-searching algorithms such as predictive text, approximate string matching, and spell checking in comparison to binary search trees.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A trie can be seen as a tree-shaped deterministic finite automaton.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries support various operations: insertion, deletion, and lookup of a string key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries are composed of nodes that contain links, which either point to other suffix child nodes or *null*.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] As for every tree, each node except the root is pointed to by only one other node, called its *parent*.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Each node contains as many links as the number of characters in the applicable alphabet (although tries tend to have a substantial number of null links).
[src:suffix-tree/trie] In some cases, the alphabet used is simply that of the character encoding—resulting in, for example, a size of 128 in the case of ASCII.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Each node contains one possible link to a prefix of strong keys of the set.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A basic structure type of nodes in the trie is as follows: ${\text{Node}}$ may contain an optional ${\text{Value}}$ , which is associated with the key that corresponds to the node.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Searching for a value in a trie is guided by the characters in the search string key, as each node in the trie contains a corresponding link to each possible character in the given string.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Thus, following the string within the trie yields the associated value for the given string key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A null link during the search indicates the inexistence of the key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The following pseudocode implements the search procedure for a given string key in a rooted trie x.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] In the above pseudocode, x and key correspond to the pointer of the trie's root node and the string key, respectively.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The search operation takes $O(m)$ time, where m is the size of the string parameter key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] In a balanced binary search tree, on the other hand, it takes $O(m\log n)$ time, in the worst case, since key needs to be compared with $O(\log n)$ other keys and each comparison takes $O(m)$ time, in the worst case.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The trie occupies less space, in comparison with a binary search tree, in the case of a large number of short strings, since nodes share common initial string subsequences and store the keys implicitly.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Insertion into a trie is guided by using the character sets as indexes to the children array until the last character of the string key is reached.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Each node in the trie corresponds to one call of the radix sorting routine, as the trie structure reflects the execution pattern of the top-down radix sort.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] If null links are encountered before reaching the last character of the string key, new nodes are created.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The input value is assigned to the value of the last node traversed, which is the node that corresponds to the key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Deletion of a key–value pair from a trie involves finding the node corresponding to the key, setting its value to null, and recursively removing nodes that have no children.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The procedure begins by examining key; an empty string indicates arrival at the node corresponding to the (original) key, in which case its value is set to null.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] If the node, then, has null value and no children, it is removed from the trie by returning null; otherwise, the node is kept by returning the node itself.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] However, tries are less efficient than a hash table when the data is directly accessed on a secondary storage device such as a hard disk drive that has higher random access time than the main memory.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries can be represented in several ways, corresponding to different trade-offs between memory use and speed of the operations.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Using a vector of pointers for representing a trie consumes enormous space; however, memory space can be reduced at the expense of running time if a singly linked list is used for each node vector, as most entries of the vector contains ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Techniques such as *alphabet reduction* may reduce the large space requirements by reinterpreting the original string as a longer string over a smaller alphabet.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] For example, a string of n bytes can alternatively be regarded as a string of 2*n* four-bit units.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] This can reduce memory usage by a factor of eight; but lookups need to visit twice as many nodes in the worst case.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Another technique includes storing a vector of 256 ASCII pointers as a bitmap of 256 bits representing ASCII alphabet, which reduces the size of individual nodes dramatically.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Bitwise tries are used to address the enormous space requirement for the trie nodes in a naive simple pointer vector implementations.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Each character in the string key set is represented via individual bits, which are used to traverse the trie over a string key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The implementations for these types of trie use vectorized CPU instructions to find the first set bit in a fixed-length key input (e.g.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] GCC's `__builtin_clz()` intrinsic function).
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Accordingly, the set bit is used to index the first item, or child node, in the 32- or 64-entry based bitwise tree.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Search then proceeds by testing each subsequent bit in the key.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] This procedure is also cache-local and highly parallelizable due to register independency, and thus performant on out-of-order execution CPUs.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Radix tree, also known as a **compressed trie**, is a space-optimized variant of a trie in which any node with only one child gets merged with its parent; elimination of branches of the nodes with a single child results in better metrics in both space and time.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] This works best when the trie remains static and set of keys stored are very sparse within their representation space.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] One more approach for static tries is to "pack" the trie by storing disjoint sets of children in the same memory location, interleaved.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Patricia trees are a particular implementation of the compressed binary trie that uses the binary encoding of the string keys in its representation.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Every node in a Patricia tree contains an index, known as a "skip number", that stores the node's branching index to avoid empty subtrees during traversal.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A naive implementation of a trie consumes immense storage due to larger number of leaf-nodes caused by the sparse distribution of keys; Patricia trees can be efficient for such cases.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A representation of a Patricia tree is shown to the right.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Each index value adjacent to the nodes represents the "skip number"—the index of the bit with which branching is to be decided.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The skip number 1 at node 0 corresponds to the position 1 in the binary encoded ASCII where the leftmost bit differed in the key set X.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The skip number is crucial for search, insertion, and deletion of nodes in the Patricia tree, and a bit masking operation is performed during every iteration.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Trie data structures are commonly used in predictive text or autocomplete dictionaries, and approximate matching algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries enable faster searches, occupy less space, especially when the set contains large number of short strings, thus used in spell checking, hyphenation applications and longest prefix match algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] However, if storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e. there is no need to store metadata associated with each word), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) or radix tree would use less storage space than a trie.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] This is because DAFSAs and radix trees can compress identical branches from the trie that correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] String dictionaries are also utilized in natural language processing, such as finding lexicon of a text corpus.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Lexicographic sorting of a set of string keys can be implemented by building a trie for the given keys and traversing the tree in pre-order fashion; this is also a form of radix sort.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries are also fundamental data structures for burstsort, which is notable for being the fastest string sorting algorithm as of 2007, accomplished by its efficient use of CPU cache.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A special kind of trie, called a suffix tree, can be used to index all suffixes in a text to carry out fast full-text searches.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] A specialized kind of trie called a compressed trie, is used in web search engines for storing the indexes - a collection of all searchable words.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Each terminal node is associated with a list of URLs—called occurrence list—to pages that match the keyword.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] The trie is stored in the main memory, whereas the occurrence is kept in an external storage, frequently in large clusters, or the in-memory index points to documents stored in an external location.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Tries are used in Bioinformatics, notably in sequence alignment software applications such as BLAST, which indexes all the different substrings of length *k* (called k-mers) of a text by storing the positions of their occurrences in a compressed trie sequence databases.
[src:suffix-tree/trie] Compressed variants of tries, such as databases for managing Forwarding Information Base (FIB), are used in storing IP address prefixes within routers and bridges for prefix-based lookup to resolve mask-based operations in IP routing.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] In computer science, **Ukkonen's algorithm** is a linear-time, online algorithm for constructing suffix trees, proposed by Esko Ukkonen in 1995.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] The algorithm begins with an implicit suffix tree containing the first character of the string.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Then it steps through the string, adding successive characters until the tree is complete.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] This order addition of characters gives Ukkonen's algorithm its "on-line" property.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] The original algorithm presented by Peter Weiner in 1973 proceeded backward from the last character to the first one from the shortest to the longest suffix.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] A simpler algorithm was found by Edward M.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] McCreight in 1976, going from the longest to the shortest suffix.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] While generating suffix tree using Ukkonen's algorithm, we will see implicit suffix tree in intermediate steps depending on characters in string S.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] In implicit suffix trees, there will be no edge with $ (or any other termination character) label and no internal node with only one edge going out of it.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Ukkonen's algorithm constructs an implicit suffix tree Ti for each prefix S[1...i] of S (S being the string of length n).
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] It first builds T1 using the 1st character, then T2 using the 2nd character, then T3 using the 3rd character, ..., Tn using the nth character.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Suffix extension is all about adding the next character into the suffix tree built so far.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] In extension j of phase i+1, algorithm finds the end of S[j...i] (which is already in the tree due to previous phase i) and then it extends S[j...i] to be sure the suffix S[j...i+1] is in the tree.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] 2. if the path from the root labelled S[j...i] ends at a non-leaf edge (i.e., there are more characters after S[i] on path) and next character is not S[i+1], then a new leaf edge with label S[i+1] and number j is created starting from character S[i+1].
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] A new internal node will also be created if S[1...i] ends inside (in between) a non-leaf edge.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] If the path from the root labelled S[j..i] ends at a non-leaf edge (i.e., there are more characters after S[i] on path) and next character is S[i+1] (already in tree), do nothing.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] One important point to note is that from a given node (root or internal), there will be one and only one edge starting from one character.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] There will not be more than one edge going out of any node starting with the same character.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] The naive implementation for generating a suffix tree going forward requires *O*(*n*2) or even *O*(*n*3) time complexity in big *O* notation, where *n* is the length of the string.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] By exploiting a number of algorithmic techniques, Ukkonen reduced this to *O*(*n*) (linear) time, for constant-size alphabets, and *O*(*n* log *n*) in general, matching the runtime performance of the earlier two algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] To better illustrate how a suffix tree is constructed using Ukkonen's algorithm, we can consider the string `S = xabxac`.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Construct $T_{1}$ for `S[1]` by adding the first character of the string.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Rule 2 applies, which creates a new leaf node.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Rule 1 applies, which extends the path label in existing leaf edge.
[src:suffix-tree/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Rule 2 applies, which creates a new leaf node (in this case, three new leaf edges and two new internal nodes are created).
